PALM OIL, TOXIC, CANINE - UK: (ENGLAND)
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 17 Nov 2015
Source: BBC News [edited]
http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-34841505


Pet dogs are at risk from palm oil washed up on beaches on the Hampshire and Dorset coast [England], dog walking groups have warned.

New Forest Dog Owners' Group said it has been alerted to 5 reports of the substance between Hengistbury Head and Milford on Sea in the past fortnight.

Dogs are vulnerable to sickness if they eat the contaminated palm oil in solid form. Local councils said any sightings should be reported.

Dog owners have been told to keep their pets away from the white waxy substance, which smells like diesel.

Kate Hurcombe from the New Forest Dog Owners' Group said: "It's not clear how much a dog has to eat before it causes a problem.

"It seems to be when there is a lot of wind so the stormy weather brings it ashore."

Several animals were poisoned when similar palm oil solids washed ashore along the South West Coast last year [2014].

Bournemouth, Christchurch and New Forest Councils urged dog walkers to report any suspected sightings of palm oil on beaches.

Palm oil has a wide variety of uses and is found in food, soaps and shampoos, and biofuels.

