[There is a wonderful picture of this at the source URL.

Due to severe storms in 2014, palm oil is now washing up on the beaches of Southern England.

Palm oil is a natural product used mainly in food processing and it can legally be released into the sea by ships. However, palm can be contaminated with fuel waste and other toxins and in solid form can be extremely harmful to dogs.

There has been concern for some years about the effects of legally dumped palm oil, but the concern is growing, not only in terms of its damage to the tourist industry but its possible ill effects on marine mammals as well as dogs on beaches.

Perhaps the 1st mention of palm oil, looking rather like chunks of lard, or perhaps waxy lard, washing ashore in the UK was in 2013.

Palm oil is very toxic to dogs and can cause vomiting and diarrhoea (as can any overload of fat) but can also cause kidney damage and liver failure. If you suspect your dog has eaten palm oil, it is crucial to get him to an emergency vet within an hour in order to ensure the best outcome, according to some UK veterinarians.

Undoubtedly the amount of palm oil to be dumped at a shipping facility could be costly, so one wonders if the regulations are likely to prohibit ocean dumping of palm oil any time soon.

Yet there are dog foods that contain small amounts of palm oil as a filler or binder and as an oil source, so surely there is a certain amount that is required to elicit effects in animals. - Mod.TG

